{{Infobox University |name = Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute |image_name = |established =1976<ref name="bpedia">{{cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Bangladesh_Agricultural_Research_Institute|title=Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute|work=banglapedia.org}}</ref> |type =[[Organization]] |staff = |faculty = |chancellor = |vice_chancellor = |students = |undergrad = |postgrad = |doctoral = |city =[[Gazipur District|Joydebpur]],<ref name="bpedia"/> [[Gazipur, Dhaka Division|Gazipur]] |province =[[Dhaka]] |country =[[Bangladesh]] |colours = |nickname =BARI |website ={{URL|www.bari.gov.bd}} }} '''Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI)''' is an autonomous organization under the [[Ministry of agriculture]], that conducts research on all crops except rice, [[jute]], sugarcane, and tea for which there are separate institutes. The central research station of the institute is at [[Joydebpur]] about {{convert|35|km}} north of [[Dhaka]].
The research compound of the central station is spread over 176 hectares of land of which 126 hectares are experiment fields. The institute has established six regional research stations in six regions of Bangladesh to develop new technologies. These research stations are located at Ishurdi, [[Jamalpur District|Jamalpur]], [[Jessore]], [[Hathazari]], Rahmatpur, and [[Akbarpur, Ramabai Nagar|Akbarpur]]. It also has 28 research stations including three hill research stations ([[Khagrachari]], [[Ramgarh Upazila|Ramgarh]] and Raikhali). Besides these, ''BARI'' has seven crop research centers, four of which are at the central research station at Joydebpur.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bari.gov.bd/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=50&Itemid=58|title=Bangladesh Agricultural Research Institute (BARI) |work=Bangladesh National Portal}}</ref>
